{{Voodoo sidebar| Religions}} {{refimprove|date=April 2008}} '''Candomblé Jejé''', also known as '''Brazilian Vodum''', is one of the major branches (''nations'') of [[Candomblé]]. It developed in the [[Portuguese Empire]] among [[Fon people|Fon]] and [[Ewe people|Ewe]] slaves. Jejé is a [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] word meaning ''stranger'', which is what the Fon and Ewe slaves represented to the Yoruba slaves.
==Vodums==
Jejé spirits are called ''Vodums'' (sing. ''Vodum''). According to tradition, they were introduced into the [[Kingdom of Dahomey]] from nearby lands by its founder [[Adja-Tado of Dahomey|King Adja-Tado]], on the advice of a ''bokono'' (seer). Their cult was reorganized and uniformized by [[Agajah of Dahomey|King Agajah]] in the 18th century.
Jejé Vodums are sometimes cultuated in houses of other nations by different names. For instance, the Vodum Dan or Bessen is called Oxumarê in [[Candomblé Ketu]]. Conversely, the Ketu Orixás may be cultuated in Jejé houses, but retain their names.
Voduns are organized into families:
{| border="0" cellpadding="2" |----- | Dan || Yewá || Fá |----- | Togun || Tohossou || Nohê Aikunguman |----- | Tobossi || Sakpata || Wealth Voduns |----- | Hevioso || Aveji-Dá || Nanã |----- | Marine Naés || Freshwater Naés || Eku and Awun |----- | Mawu-Lisa || Hohos || - |}
