'''Double belonging''' is the phenomenon in which one claims to be an adherent of two different religions at the same time or incorporates the practices of another religion into their own faith life.<ref name="Fox2010">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/double-belonging-buddhism-and-christian-faith|title=Double belonging: Buddhism and Christian faith|last=Fox|first=Thomas C.|date=23 June 2010|publisher=[[National Catholic Reporter]]|language=English|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref> It is increasing in certain parts of [[Europe]] and [[North America]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=McDaniel|first=Jay|year=2003|title=Double Religious Belonging: A Process Approach|journal=Buddhist-Christian Studies|publisher=University of Hawai'i Press|volume=23|pages=67–76}}</ref><ref name="Fox2010"/> One such example is a person [[church attendance|attending a Christian church]] but also engaging in the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] practice of [[yoga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.christiancentury.org/article/2011-01/double-belonging|title=Double belonging: One person, two faiths|last=Frykholm|first=Amy|date=14 January 2011|publisher=[[The Christian Century]]|language=English|accessdate=3 October 2017}}</ref>

