===Pilgrimages===
{{Main|Tirtha (Jainism)}}
Jain ''Tirtha'' ("pilgrim") sites are divided into the following categories:{{sfn|Titze|1998|p=}}
* ''Siddhakshetra''{{snds}}Site of the [[Moksha (Jainism)|''moksha'']] of an ''arihant'' (''kevalin'') or ''tirthankara'', such as: [[Mount Kailash|Ashtapada]], [[Shikharji]], [[Girnar]], [[Pawapuri]], [[Palitana]], [[Mangi-Tungi]], and [[Champapuri]] (capital of [[Anga]]).
* ''Atishayakshetra''{{snds}}Locations where divine events have occurred, such as: [[Mahavirji]], [[Rishabhdeo]], [[Kundalpur]], [[Tijara Jain Temple|Tijara]], and [[Aharji]].
* ''Puranakshetra''{{snds}} Places associated with the lives of great men, such as: [[Ayodhya]], [[Vidisha]], [[Hastinapur]], and [[Rajgir]].
* ''Gyanakshetra''{{snds}} Places associated with famous ''[[acharya]]s'', or centers of learning, such as [[Shravanabelagola]].

Outside contemporary India, Jain communities built temples in locations such as [[Nagarparkar]], [[Sindh]] ([[Pakistan]]). However, according to a UNESCO tentative world heritage site application, Nagarparkar was not a "major religious centre or a place of pilgrimage" for Jainism, but it was once an important cultural landscape before "the last remaining Jain community left the area in 1947 at Partition".<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/6111/ Nagarparkar Cultural Landscape], Tantative List, UNESCO World Heritage Centre</ref>

===Statues and sculptures===
{{Main|Jain sculpture}}

Jain sculptures are mainly images depicting ''tīrthaṅkaras''. A sculpture could depict any of the twenty-four ''tīrthaṅkaras{{'}}s'' images. Parshvanatha, Rishabhanatha and Mahāvīra are among the more popular. These ''tīrthaṅkaras'' usually depicted in the lotus position or ''kayotsarga''.{{sfn|Arora||p=405}} Sculptures of ''chaumukha'' ("quadruple") images are also popular in Jainism. Sculptures of Arihant, [[Bahubali]], and protector deities like [[Ambika (Jainism)|Ambika]] are also found. ''Tirthanakar'' idols look similar and are differentiated by the symbol belonging to each ''tirthanakar'' except Parshvanatha. Statues of Parshvanath have a snake crown on head. There are a few differences between the Digambara and the Śvētāmbara depictions of idols.{{sfn|Cort|2010}} Digambara images are naked without any beautification, whereas Śvētāmbara depictions are clothed and decorated with temporary ornaments.{{sfn|Cort|2010}}

A monolithic, {{convert|18|m|ft|adj=on|abbr=off}} statue of Bahubali, referred to as ''[[Gommateshvara]]'', built in 981 CE by the Ganga minister and commander [[Chavundaraya]], is situated on a hilltop in Shravanabelagola in the [[Hassan district]] of Karnataka state. This statue was voted first in the SMS poll Seven Wonders of India conducted by ''[[The Times of India]]''.<ref>{{citation |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/2256323.cms |title=And India's 7 wonders are |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date= 5 August 2007}}</ref> The [[Statue of Ahiṃsā]] (depicting Rishabhanatha) was erected in the [[Nashik district]] in 2015; it is {{convert|33|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall.<ref>{{citation |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nashik/70-crore-plan-for-idol-installation-at-Mangi-Tungi/articleshow/50037188.cms |title=70-crore plan for idol installation at Mangi-Tungi |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=4 December 2015 |last=Botekar |first=Abhilash |agency=TNN |location=[[Nashik]] }}</ref> Idols made from ''[[Ashtadhatu]]'' (literally "eight metals"), [[Akota Bronzes|Akota Bronze]], [[brass]], [[gold]], [[silver]], stone [[monolith]]s, [[Rock-cut architecture|rock cut]], and precious stones are popular in Jainism.<ref>{{Citation|url={{Google books|clUmKaWRFTkC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|title=Indian Sculpture: Circa 500 B.C.-A.D. 700|publisher=Los Angeles County Museum of Art|first=Pratapaditya|last=Pal|p=22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/jais/hd_jais.htm|title=Met Museum}}</ref>

A large number of ''ayagapata'', [[votive]] tablets for offerings and the worship of ''tīrthankara'', were excavated from [[Kankali Tila]], [[Mathura]]. These sculptures date from the 2nd century BCE to the 12th century CE.{{sfn|Jain|Fischer|1978|pp=9–10}}

===Symbols===
{{Main|Jain symbols}}
[[File:Jain Prateek Chihna.svg|thumb|upright=0.8|The Jain emblem]]
Jain icons and arts incorporate symbols such as swastika, om, and the ''Ashtamangala''.

====Swastika====
The [[swastika]] is an important Jain symbol. Its four arms symbolise the four realms of existence in which rebirth occurs according to Jainism: humans, heavenly beings, hellish beings and non-humans (plants and animals).{{sfn|Cort|2001a|p=17}}{{sfn|Jansma|Jain|2006|p=123}} This is conceptually similar to the six realms of rebirth represented by ''[[bhavachakra]]'' in Buddhism.{{sfn|Cort|2001a|p=17}} It is usually shown with three dots on the top, which represent the three jewels mentioned in ancient texts such as ''Tattvartha sūtra'' and ''Uttaradhyayana sūtra'': correct faith, correct understanding and correct conduct. These jewels are the means believed in Jainism to lead one to the state of spiritual perfection, a state that is symbolically represented by a crescent and one dot on top representing the liberated soul.{{sfn|Cort|2001a|pp=17-18}}

====Symbol of ''Ahiṃsā''====
The hand with a wheel on the palm symbolizes [[Ahimsa in Jainism|''ahimsā'' in Jainism]] with ''ahiṃsā'' written in the middle. The wheel represents the ''[[dharmachakra]]'' ("Wheel of the Dharma"), which stands for the resolve to halt the ''saṃsāra'' ("wandering") through the relentless pursuit of ''ahimsā'' ("compassion").

====''Om''====
[[File:Om_jaïn_orange.svg|thumb|upright=0.45|[[Om#Jainism|Om]] in Jainism]]
In Jainism, [[Om#Jainism|''Om'']] is considered a condensed form of reference to the ''Pañca-Parameṣṭhi'', by their initials ''A+A+A+U+M'' (''{{IAST|o[[pluti|3]]}}{{IAST|m}}''). According to the ''[[Dravyasamgraha]]'' by Acharya [[Nemicandra]], ''AAAUM'' (or just ''Om'') is a one syllable short form of the initials of the five parameshthis: "''Arihant'', ''[[Ashiri]]'', ''[[Acharya]]'', ''[[Upajjhaya]]'', ''Muni''".<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.cs.colostate.edu/~malaiya/om.html |title=Om – significance in Jainism, Languages and Scripts of India, Colorado State University|work=cs.colostate.edu }}</ref>{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|pp=410–411}} The ''Om'' symbol is also used in ancient Jain scriptures to represent the five lines of the [[Namokara Mantra|''Ṇamōkāra'' Mantra]].{{Sfn|Agarwal|2012|p=135}}{{Sfn|Agarwal|2013|p=80}}

====Jain emblem====
In 1974, on the 2500th anniversary of the nirvana of Mahāvīra, the Jain community chose one image as an emblem to be the main identifying symbol for Jainism.{{Sfn|Robinson|2006|p=225}} The overall shape depicts the three ''loka'' ("realms of rebirth") of Jain cosmology i.e., heaven, human world and hell. The semi-circular topmost portion symbolizes ''Siddhashila'', which is a zone beyond the three realms. The Jain swastika is present in the top portion, and the symbol of ''Ahiṃsā'' in the lower portion. At the bottom of the emblem is the Jain mantra, ''[[Parasparopagraho Jivanam|Parasparopagraho Jīvānām]]''. According to Vilas Sangave, the mantra means "all life is bound together by mutual support and interdependence".{{sfn|Sangave|2001|p=123}} According to Anne Vallely, this mantra is from sūtra 5.21 of Umaswati's ''Tattvarthasūtra'', and it means "souls render service to one another".<ref>{{cite book|author=Anne Vallely|editor=Stephen Bullivant and Michael Ruse|title=The Oxford Handbook of Atheism|url={{Google books|93VoAgAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-166739-8|page=358}}</ref>

==== Jain flag ====
[[File:Jain flag.jpg|thumb|Jain Flag]]
The five colours of the [[Jain flag]] represent the ''[[Pañca-Parameṣṭhi]]'' and the five vows, small as well as great:{{sfn|Vijay K. Jain|2012|p=iv}}
* White – represents the ''[[Arihant (Jainism)|arihants]]'', souls who have conquered all passions (anger, attachments, aversion) and have attained omniscience and eternal bliss through self-realisation. It also denotes peace or ''[[Ahimsa in Jainism|ahiṃsā]]'' ("non-violence ").
* Red – represents the ''[[Siddha]]'', souls that have attained salvation and truth. It also denotes ''satya''  ("truthfulness")
* Yellow – represents the [[Acharya (Jainism)|''acharya'']] the Masters of Adepts. The colour also stands for ''achaurva'' ("non-stealing").
* Green – represents the ''[[upadhyaya]]'' ("adepts"), those who teach scriptures to monks. It also signifies ''[[brahmacharya]]'' ("chastity").
* Black – represents the [[Jain ascetics]].  It also signifies ''[[aparigraha]]'' ("non-possession").

====''Ashtamangala''====
The ''[[Ashtamangala]]'' are a set of eight auspicious symbols, which are different in the Digambara and Śvētāmbar traditions.{{sfn|Titze|1998|p=234}}

In the Digambara tradition, the eight auspicious symbols are [[Chatra (umbrella)|Chatra]], ''[[Dhvaja]]'', ''[[Kalasha]]'', [[Chaamara]], [[Mirror]], Chair, [[Hand fan]] and Vessel. In the Śvētāmbar tradition, these are Swastika, ''[[Srivatsa]]'', ''[[Nandavarta]]'', ''Vardhmanaka'' ("food vessel"), ''Bhadrasana'' ("seat"), ''[[Kalasha]]'' ("pot"), ''Darpan'' ("mirror") and pair of fish.{{Sfn|Titze|1998|p=234}}

==History==
{{Main|History of Jainism}}
[[File:Photo of lord adinath bhagwan at kundalpur.JPG|thumb|[[Rishabhanatha|Rishabhdev]], believed to have lived over a million years ago, is considered the traditional founder of Jainism.]]

===Origins===
{{See also|Timeline of Jainism|Śramaṇa}}

The origins of Jainism are obscure.{{sfn|Rankin|Mardia|2013|p=975}}{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=13}} The Jains claim their religion to be eternal, and consider [[Rishabhanatha]] to be the founder in the present time-cycle, the first of 24 Jain ''tirthankaras'' in Jain belief, and someone who lived for 8,400,000 purva years.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=16}} According to one hypothesis, such as one by [[Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan]], the first vice president of India, Jainism was in existence before the Vedas were composed.{{sfn|Jambuvijaya|2002|p=114}}{{sfn|Pande|1957|p=353}} According to historians, the first 22 of the 24 ''tirthankaras'' were mythical figures. These figures were supposed to have lived more than 85,000 years ago. They were five to hundred times taller than average human beings and lived for thousands of years.<ref>{{citation | title= Rishabhanatha, in ''Encyclopaedia Britannica'' | url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Rishabhanatha |publisher=Editors of the Encyclopaedia Britannica |year=2010 }}</ref>{{sfn|Sangave|2001|pp=104, 129}}{{sfn|Saraswati|1908|p=444}} The 23rd ''tirthankara'', [[Parshvanatha]], is generally accepted to be based on an ancient historic human being{{sfn|Zimmer|1953|pp=183}}<ref>{{citation |first=Paul |last=Dundas |title=Jainism |publisher=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |date=2013 |url= http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/299478/Jainism }}</ref>{{sfn|Jaini|1998|p=10}} of uncertain dates, possibly 8th–7th century BCE.

Some confessional Jain scholars such as Parikh have argued that some images such as those of the bull in [[Indus Valley Civilization]] seal may be related to Jainism, but such claims are highly speculative and a subjective interpretation. This theory has not been accepted by most scholars because very little is known about the Indus Valley iconography and script.{{sfn|Long|2013|pp=53-54}} Jainism, like Buddhism, is one of the ''[[Sramana]]'' traditions of ancient India, those that rejected the [[Veda]]s and developed their own scriptures.{{sfn|Lochtefeld|2002|p=639}}<ref>P. Billimoria (1988), Śabdapramāṇa: Word and Knowledge, Studies of Classical India Volume 10, Springer, {{ISBN|978-94-010-7810-8}}, pages 1-30</ref>

There is inscriptional evidence for the presence of Jain monks in south India by the second or first centuries BC, and archaeological evidence of Jain monks in Saurashtra in Gujarat by the second century CE.{{sfn|Cort|2010|p=202}} Statues of Jain ''tirthankara'' have been found dating back to second century BC.{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2016|p=444}}

===Political history===
[[File:Udayagiri Caves - Rani Gumpha 01.jpg|thumb|[[Udayagiri and Khandagiri Caves]] built by [[King Kharavela]] of [[Mahameghavahana dynasty]] in 2nd century BCE]]
Information regarding the political history of Jainism is uncertain and fragmentary. Jains consider the king [[Bimbisara]] (c. 558–491 BCE), [[Ajatashatru]] (c. 492–460 BCE), and [[Udayin]] (c. 460-440 BCE) of the [[Haryanka dynasty]] as a patron of Jainism.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=41}}

Jain tradition states that [[Chandragupta Maurya]] (322–298 BCE), the founder of the [[Mauryan Empire]] and grandfather of [[Ashoka]], became a monk and disciple of Jain ascetic [[Bhadrabahu]] during later part of his life. According to historians, Chandragupta's story appears in various versions in Buddhist, Jain, and Hindu texts.{{sfn|Mookerji|1988|pp=4–21, 232–237}} Broadly, Chandragupta was born into a humble family, abandoned, raised as a son by another family, then with the training and counsel of Chanakya of ''[[Arthashastra]]'' fame ultimately built one of the largest empires in ancient India.<ref name=britchandrag>[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Chandragupta Chandragupta Maurya, EMPEROR OF INDIA], Encyclopaedia Britannica</ref><ref name="Rothermund2004p63"/><ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Roger Boesche|author=Roger Boesche|title=The First Great Political Realist: Kautilya and His Arthashastra|url={{Google books|K85NA7Rg67wC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2003|publisher=Lexington Books|isbn=978-0-7391-0607-5|pages=7–18}}</ref> According to Jain history, late in his life, Chandragupta renounced the empire he built and handed over his power to his son, became a Jaina monk, and headed to meditate and pursue spirituality in the Deccan region, under the Jaina teacher Bhadrabahu at Shravanabelagola.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=42}} There state Jain texts, he died by fasting, a Jaina ascetic method of ending one's life by choice (''Sallenkana vrata'').<ref name=britchandrag/>{{sfn|Mookerji|1988|pp=39–46, 234-236}}<ref name="Rothermund2004p63">{{cite book|author1=Hermann Kulke|author2=Dietmar Rothermund|title=A History of India|url={{Google books|RoW9GuFJ9GIC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2004|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-32920-0|pages=63–65}}</ref> The 3rd century BCE emperor Ashoka, in his pillar edicts, mentions several ancient Indian religious groups including the ''Niganthas'' (Jaina).{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=43}}

According to another Jain legend, King [[Salivahana]] of the late 1st century CE was a patron of Jainism, as were many others in the early centuries of the 1st millennium CE. But von Glasenapp states that the historicity of these stories is difficult to establish.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=51}} Archeological evidence suggests that Mathura was an important Jain centre between the 2nd century BCE and the 5th century CE. Inscriptions from the 1st and 2nd century CE show that the schism between Digambara and Śvētāmbara had already taken place.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=49}}

King Harshavardhana of the 7th century grew up in [[Shaivism]], following his family, but he championed Jainism, Buddhism and all traditions of Hinduism.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=52}} King Ama of the 8th century converted to Jainism, and the Jaina pilgrimage tradition was well established in his era.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|pp=52-54}} Mularaja, the founder of [[Chalukya dynasty]], constructed a Jain temple, even though he was not a Jain.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|p=56}}

In the second half of the 1st century CE, Hindu kings sponsored and helped build major Jaina cave temples. For example, the Hindu [[Rashtrakuta]] dynasty started the early group of Jain temples,<ref name=pereira21>{{cite book|author=José Pereira|title=Monolithic Jinas|url={{Google books|LMTgiygj4-oC|page=PA24|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|year=1977|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-2397-6|pages=21–24}}</ref> and the [[Seuna (Yadava) dynasty|Yadava dynasty]] built many of the middle and later Jain group of temples at the [[Ellora Caves]] between 700 and 1000 CE.<ref name=asiintro>[http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_whs_ellora.asp World Heritage Sites - Ellora Caves], Archeological Survey of India (2011), Government of India</ref><ref name=Madan>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= 178|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref><ref name="Owen2012p10">{{cite book|author=Lisa Owen|title=Carving Devotion in the Jain Caves at Ellora|url={{Google books|vHK2WE8xAzYC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2012|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=978-9004206298|pages=1–10}}</ref>

===Interaction with other religions===
[[File:Shrine with Four Jinas (Rishabhanatha (Adinatha)), Parshvanatha, Neminatha, and Mahavira) LACMA M.85.55 (1 of 4).jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|''Chaumukha'' Sculpture with Four Jinas (Rishabhanatha (Adinatha), Parshvanatha, Neminatha, and Mahavira), LACMA, 6th century]]
Mahāvīra and Buddha are generally accepted as contemporaries (circa 5th century BCE).{{sfn|Dundas|2003a|p=383}}<ref name=keown127>{{cite book|author1=Damien Keown|author2=Charles S. Prebish|title=Encyclopedia of Buddhism |url={{Google books|NFpcAgAAQBAJ|page=PA127|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-98588-1|pages=127–130}}</ref> The interaction between Jainism and Buddhism began with the Buddha. Buddhist texts refer to Mahāvīra as ''Nigantha Nataputta''.{{sfn|Sangave|2001|p=105}}

Beyond the times of the Mahāvīra and the Buddha, the two ascetic ''sramana'' ("seeker") religions competed for followers as well as the merchant trade networks that sustained them.{{sfn|Hirakawa|1993|pp=4–7}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Jason Neelis|title=Early Buddhist Transmission and Trade Networks: Mobility and Exchange Within and Beyond the Northwestern Borderlands of South Asia|url={{Google books|GB-JV2eOr2UC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2010|publisher=BRILL Academic|isbn=90-04-18159-8|pages=72–76}}</ref> Their mutual interaction, along with those of Hindu traditions, have been significant. In some cases the titles of the Buddhist and Jaina texts are the same or similar but present different doctrines.{{sfn|Dundas|2003b|pp=ix–xi, 151–162}}

Royal patronage has been a key factor in the growth as well as the decline of Jainism.{{sfn|Natubhai Shah|2004|pp=69–70}} The Pallava King [[Mahendravarman I]] (600{{nsndns}}630 CE) converted from Jainism to Shaivism under the influence of [[Appar]].{{sfn|Lochtefeld|2002|p=409}} His work ''[[Mattavilasa Prahasana]]'' ridicules certain Shaiva sects and the Buddhists and also expresses contempt towards Jain ascetics.{{sfn|Arunachalam|1981|p=170}} Sambandar converted the contemporary [[Pandyan Dynasty|Pandya]] king to Shaivism. During the 11th century, [[Basava]], a minister to the Jain [[Kalachuris of Kalyani|Kalachuri]] king [[Bijjala II|Bijjala]], succeeded in converting numerous Jains to the [[Lingayatism|Lingayat]] Shaivite sect. The Lingayats destroyed various temples belonging to Jains and adapted them to their use.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|pp=75–77}} The [[Hoysala Dynasty|Hoysala]] King [[Vishnuvardhana]] (c.{{nbsp}}1108{{nsndns}}1152 CE) became a follower of the [[Vaishnava]] sect under the influence of [[Ramanuja]], after which Vaishnavism grew rapidly in what is now Karnataka.{{sfn|Das|2005|p=161}}

[[File:La grotte Jain Indra Sabha Ellora Caves, India.jpg|thumb|left|The Indra Sabha cave at the [[Ellora Caves]], are co-located with Hindu and Buddhist monuments.]]
Jainism and Hinduism influenced each other. Jain texts declare some of the Hindu gods as blood relatives of legendary ''tirthankara''. Neminatha, the 22nd ''tirthankara'' for example is presented as a cousin of Krishna in Jain Puranas and other texts.<ref name=britneminatha>[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Arishtanemi Arishtanemi: JAINA SAINT], Encyclopaedia Britannica</ref>{{sfn|Long|2009|p=42}} However, Jain scholars such as [[Haribhadra]] also wrote satires about Hindu gods, mocking them with novel outrageous stories where the gods misbehave and act unethically.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=236-237}}<ref>{{cite book|author=John R. Hinnells|title=Who's Who of World Religions|url={{Google books|CDSxCwAAQBAJ|page=PA145|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|year=1991|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-1-349-09500-1|pages=145–146}}</ref> The Hindu gods are presented by some Jain writers as persecuting, tempting, afraid of, or serving a legendary Jina before he gains omniscience. In other stories, one or more Jinas easily defeat the Hindu deities such as [[Vishnu]], or [[Rama]] and [[Sita]] who come to pay respect to a Jina at a major Jain pilgrimage site such as Mount Satrunjaya.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=113-115, 222-223, 236-237}}

The Jain and Hindu communities have often been very close and mutually accepting. Some Hindu temples have included a Jain ''Tirthankara'' within its premises in a place of honour.{{sfn|Long|2009|pp=5-6}}<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ramesh Chandra Sharma|author2=Pranati Ghosal|title=Jaina Contribution to Varanasi |url={{Google books|YoLXAAAAMAAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2006|publisher=Jnanapravaha|isbn=978-81-246-0341-3|pages=100–103}}</ref> Similarly numerous temple complexes feature both Hindu and Jain monuments, with [[Badami cave temples]] and [[Khajuraho]] among some of the most well known.{{Sfn|Michell|2014|p=38-52, 60-61}}<ref>Trudy King et al., Asia and Oceania: International Dictionary of Historic Places, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1884964046}}, pages 468-470</ref>

[[File:Gori_Mandar.jpg|alt=Jain monuments in Nagarparkar, Pakistan|thumb|The ruins of [[Godiji#The original Gori Temple (گوری مندر) in Tharparkar|Gori Jain temples]] in [[Nagarparkar]], Pakistan, a pilgrimage site before 1947.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/6111/|title=Nagarparkar Cultural Landscape – UNESCO World Heritage Centre|last=Centre|first=UNESCO World Heritage|website=whc.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref>]]
Jainism faced persecution during and after the [[Muslim conquests on the Indian subcontinent]].{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=145-146, 124}} Muslims rulers, such as [[Mahmud Ghazni]] (1001), [[Mohammad Ghori]] (1175) and [[Alauddin Khalji|Ala-ud-din Muhammed Shah Khalji]] (1298) further oppressed the Jain community.{{sfn|von Glasenapp|1925|pp=74–75}} They vandalised idols and destroyed temples or converted them into mosques. They also burned Jain books and killed Jains. There were significant exceptions, such as Emperor [[Akbar]] (1542{{nsndns}}1605) whose legendary religious tolerance, out of respect for Jains, ordered the release of caged birds and banned the killing of animals on the Jain festival of Paryusan.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=146}} After Akbar, Jains faced an intense period of Muslim persecution in the 17th century.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=220-221}}<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Truschke|first=Audrey|date=2015-09-01|title=Dangerous Debates: Jain responses to theological challenges at the Mughal court*|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/modern-asian-studies/article/dangerous-debates-jain-responses-to-theological-challenges-at-the-mughal-court/8A3F928B34C46E3583FF6577968805A4|journal=Modern Asian Studies|volume=49|issue=5|pages=1311–1344|doi=10.1017/S0026749X14000055|issn=0026-749X}}</ref>

The Jain community were the traditional bankers and financiers, and this significantly impacted the Muslim rulers. However, they rarely were a part of the political power during the Islamic rule period of the Indian subcontinent.{{sfn|Cort|1998|pp=85-86}}

===Colonial era===
Colonial era reports and Christian missions variously viewed Jainism as either a sect of Hinduism<ref>{{cite book|author=British India|title=Various Census of India: 1871-1872|url={{Google books|4AEJAAAAQAAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=1867|publisher=Government of India|pages=31 note 140}}</ref> or Buddhism, or as a distinct religion.<ref>{{cite book|author=Edward Washburn Hopkins|title=The Religions of India|url={{Google books|O0IvAAAAYAAJ|page=PA283|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|year=1902|publisher=Ginn & Company|page=283}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=A.J. Sunavala|title=Adarsha Sadhu: An Ideal Monk|url={{Google books|oUU4AAAAIAAJ|page=PA91|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|year=1934|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-00-140429-5|pages=91–93}}</ref> According to Padmanath Jaini, Christian missionaries expressed extreme frustration at Jain people without pagan creator gods refusing to convert to Christianity, while colonial era Jain scholars such as [[Champat Rai Jain]] defended Jainism against criticism and misrepresentation by Christian activists.{{sfn|Jaini|2000|p=33}} Missionaries of Christianity and Islam considered Jain traditions as idolatrous and a false religion,<ref>{{cite book|author=Rosalind I. J. Hackett|title=Proselytization Revisited: Rights Talk, Free Markets and Culture Wars|url={{Google books|ZHHXAAAAMAAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} |year=2008|publisher=Equinox Academic|isbn=978-1-84553-227-7|pages=63–68}}</ref> characterizing Jain temples and icons, such of those of Jina, as false idols and superstitious practices. These criticisms, states [[John E. Cort|John Cort]], were flawed and also ignored similar practices within sects of Christianity.{{sfn|Cort|2010|pp=12-16, 200-207, 218-219, 251 with note 10}}

The British colonial government in India, as well as Indian princely states, passed laws that made monks roaming naked in streets a crime, one that led to arrest. This law particularly impacted the Digambara monks.{{sfn|Flügel|2006|pp=348–349}} The Akhil Bharatiya Jaina Samaj opposed this law, and argued that it interfered with the religious rights of Jains. Acharya [[Shantisagar]] entered Bombay (now Mumbai) in 1927, but was forced to cover his body. He then led an India-wide tour as the naked monk with his followers, to various Digambara sacred sites, and was welcomed by kings of the Maharashtra provinces.{{sfn|Flügel|2006|pp=348–349}} Shantisagar fasted to oppose the restrictions imposed on Digambara monks by the [[British Raj]] and prompted their discontinuance.{{sfn|Natubhai Shah|2004|p=56}} The colonial era laws that banned naked monks remained effective through World War II, but they were abolished by independent India after it gained independence.{{sfn|Flügel|2006|pp=359–360}}

==Jains in the modern era==
{{Main|Jain community}}
[[File:Pakbirra Jain Shrine of Purulia 03.jpg|thumb|Ancient [[Purulia district#Tourism|temple of Pakbirra, Purulia]] ]]
Followers of the path practised by the Jinas are known as Jains.{{sfn|Sangave|2006|p=15}}{{sfn|Upinder Singh|2016|p=313}} The majority of Jains currently reside in India. With four to five million followers worldwide,{{sfn|Melton|Baumann|2010|p=lix, 1395}} Jainism is relatively small compared to [[Major religious groups|major world religions]]. Jains form 0.37% of [[Jainism in India|India]]'s population. Most of them are concentrated in the states of [[Jainism in Maharashtra|Maharashtra]] (1.4 million in 2011,<ref name=jaindemographics/> 31.46% of Indian Jains), [[Jainism in Rajasthan|Rajasthan]] (13.97%), [[Jainism in Gujarat|Gujarat]] (13.02%) and [[Madhya Pradesh]] (12.74%). [[Jainism in Karnataka|Karnataka]] (9.89%), [[Jainism in Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh]] (4.79%), [[Jainism in Delhi|Delhi]] (3.73%) and [[Tamil Jain|Tamil Nadu]] (2.01%) also have significant Jain populations.<ref name=jaindemographics>{{citation |url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/c-01.html |title=C-1 Population By Religious Community |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |last=Office of registrar general and census commissioner |date=2011 }}</ref> Outside India, Jain communities can be found in [[Jainism in Europe|Europe]], the [[Jainism in the United States|United States]], [[Jainism in Canada|Canada]],{{sfn|Wiley|2009|p=43}} [[Australia]] and [[Jainism in Africa|Kenya]].{{sfn|Mugambi|2010|p=108}}

According to the National Family and Health Survey (NFHS-4) conducted in 2015-16, Jains form the wealthiest community in India.<ref>[https://m.hindustantimes.com/india-news/delhi-and-punjab-richest-states-jain-wealthiest-community-national-survey/story-sakdd3MBOfKhU2p5LrNVUM.html Delhi and Punjab richest states, Jain wealthiest community: National survey]</ref> Jains have the highest literacy rate (87%) in India, in the 7-years to oldest age group, according to its 2011 census. The Jaina community also has the highest number of college graduates.<ref>{{citation |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Jains-have-highest-percentage-of-literates-Census-data/articleshow/53942863.cms |title=Jains have highest percentage of literates: Census 2011 |publisher=[[The Times of India]] |date=31 August 2016 }}</ref> Excluding the retired senior citizens, Jain literacy rate in India exceeded 97%. The female to male child sex ratio in the 0-6 year age was second lowest for Jains (870 girls per 1,000 boys), higher than [[Sikhism|Sikhs]] in India. Further, Jain males have the highest work participation rates, while Jain females have the lowest work participation rates in India.<ref>{{citation| url=http://censusindia.gov.in/Ad_Campaign/drop_in_articles/04-Distribution_by_Religion.pdf| title=Distribution of Population by Religions| author=Census India|publisher=Government of India|year=2011}}</ref>

Major Jain communities:
[[File:Deogarh,_UP._Jain_temple_complex.jpg|thumb|Jain Temple complex, [[Deogarh, Uttar Pradesh|Deogarh]] ]]
* [[Jain Bunt]] are a [[Jain]] community from [[Karnataka]], [[India]].<ref name="singh">{{cite book|last=Kumar Suresh Singh, Anthropological Survey of India|title=People of India: Maharashtra, Volume 1|year=2004|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7991-100-6|pages=387–391(Emigrant Bunts by P. Dhar)}}</ref>
* Jain [[Komati caste|Komati]] is a small community scattered all over South and Central India and patrons of many Jain Institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jainsamaj.org/rpg_site/literature2.php?id=614&cat=42|title=Jain Culture In Telugu Literature |website=www.jainsamaj.org|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207000251/http://www.jainsamaj.org/rpg_site/literature2.php?id=614&cat=42|archivedate=7 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/Inscription-on-the-last-Jain-temple-in-Telangana-found/article14427991.ece|title=Inscription on the last Jain temple in Telangana found|website=thehindu.com}}</ref>
* [[Saraks]] is a community in [[Jharkhand]], [[Bihar]], [[Bengal]], and [[Orissa, India|Orissa]]. They have been followers of Jainism since ancient time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anagrasarkalyan.gov.in/htm/obc_list.html |title=Government of West Bengal: List of Other Backward Classes |publisher=Govt. of West Bengal |date= |accessdate=December 23, 2011}}</ref>
* [[Porwal]]  community that originated in southern [[Rajasthan]], India.<ref name="Bhanu2004">{{cite book|author=Anthropological Survey of India|editor=K. S. Singh|title=People of India: Maharashtra|url={{Google books|4bfmnmsBfQ4C|page=PA1738|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|year=2004|publisher=Popular Prakashan|location=Mumbai, India|isbn=978-81-7991-102-0|page=1738}}</ref>
* [[Parwar (Jain community)|Parwar]] is a major [[Jain]] community from the [[Jainism in Bundelkhand|Bundelkhand region]], which is largely in [[Madhya Pradesh]] and [[Lalitpur District, India|Lalitpur District, Jhansi]].<ref name="auto">{{citation|url={{Google books|OmBjoAFMfjoC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|title=People of India|edition=Maharashtra, Part 1|first=Kumar Suresh|last=Singh|publisher=Popular Prakashan|date=2004|isbn=9788179911006|p=565}}</ref>
* [[Agrawal Jain]] of [[Hisar, Haryana]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}
* [[Bhabra]] of [[Punjab region|Punjab]] is an ancient merchant community from Punjab region which mainly follows Jainism.
* [[Sarawagi]] or ''Khandelwali'' originated from [[Khandela]], a historical town in northern [[Rajasthan]].<ref name="auto"/>
* [[Bagherwal]] from [[Baghera]] (currently known as [[Ajmer district]]) a princely state in [[Rajasthan]], a community of Digambar sect.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}
* [[Shrimal Jain|Shrimal]], originally from [[Rajasthan]], [[Shrimal]] town in southern [[Rajasthan]]. The Shrimal (Srimal) Jain are part of the [[Oswal]] merchant and minister caste that is found primarily in the north of India.<ref>{{citation|url={{Google books|vm_KCE4XXPMC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|title=People of India|edition=Rajasthan|first=K.S.|last=Singh|publisher=Popular Prakashan|date=1989|isbn=9788171547692|p=524}}</ref>
* [[Oswal]] are a [[Jain]] community with origins in the [[Marwar]] region of [[Rajasthan]] and [[Tharparkar district]] in [[Sindh]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Alchemies of Violence: Myths of Identity and the Life of Trade in Western India |first=Lawrence A. |last=Babb |publisher=SAGE |year=2004 |isbn=9780761932239 |pages=164–178 |url={{Google books|74tUY0le33UC|page=PA164|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref>
* [[Jaiswal Jain|Jaiswal]] are mainly located in the [[Gwalior]] and [[Agra]] region.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}
* [[Navnat]] emerged as a result of blending of several smaller Jain communities in East Africa as well as in Gujarat itself in early 20th century.<ref>{{Citation|url={{Google books|PQPqCgAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}}|title=Indian Africa: Minorities of Indian-Pakistani Origin in Eastern Africa|first=Michel|last=Adam|publisher=Mkuki na Nyota Publishers|date=2015|isbn=9789987082971|p=299}}</ref>

Jainism has been praised for some of its practices and beliefs.
[[Mahatma Gandhi]], who was greatly influenced by Jainism, said:{{sfn|Rudolph|Rudolph|1984|p=171}}
{{quote|No religion in the World has explained the principle of ''Ahiṃsā'' so deeply and systematically as is discussed with its applicability in every human life in Jainism. As and when the benevolent principle of ''Ahiṃsā'' or non-violence will be ascribed for practice by the people of the world to achieve their end of life in this world and beyond, Jainism is sure to have the uppermost status and Mahāvīra is sure to be respected as the greatest authority on ''Ahiṃsā''.{{sfn|Janardan Pandey|1998|p=50}}}}

